qx||cs|6|fp|1|ht|b|at|^-{      GENERAL APPROACH; 2@C OPENING (PART 2)      
  Larry Cohen - Date of publish: 1/15/2014 - Level: Intermediate  }
^-|cs||fp||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|Last month, we discussed our general system approach and the parameters for a strong 2@C opening. This month, we explore the follow-ups after the 2@C opening.|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


AT|

I frequently get asked about this. I give my usual answer: "There are many methods--all with good and bad attributes. Just pick one and live with it. It is not too important which method--as long as your partner knows it and is playing the same way!" I do, however, have a strong preference for one method over the other.|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


AT|

Some people use control (or "step") responses. I've never been a big fan. Others use 2@D as "negative." This strikes me as a poor approach. I prefer to use 2@D as "waiting." It could be a zero-count, but it also could be quite a good hand. More on this in a moment. Another method is to use 2@H as negative (0-3) and 2@D as an artificial positive game-force. This is okay, but not what I recommend. Let's examine the most common (by far) method (and the one I do recommend):|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


cs|6|AT|

^-{    2C-2D Waiting    }
^-|at|^B@2
Using 2@C-2@D waiting, you will find that on almost all hands the response is 2@D. When would you not respond 2@D? With a good hand and a good 5 card suit, you can respond in the suit. What is "good?" At least 8 HCP and usually 2 of the top 4 honors. I would not respond in a suit of Axxxx or K10xxx. I would not make a positive response with only 6 HCP even if the suit were good enough. If I don't have a good 5+ card suit and 8 HCP, I respond 2@D--waiting. (I would never respond 2NT even with notrump shape/stoppers/points--risking playing notrump from the wrong side and also taking away opener's room).|
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


AT|

So, a 2@D response shows "^*Bany hand that lacks 8 HCP and a good 5+ card suit.^*N" It can be a balanced 14-count! It can be a 0-count. Let s look at some examples of 2@D responses to 2@C (using 2@D as "waiting:)|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


