cs|6|fp|1|ht|b|at|^-{      Fast Arrival     }
^-|cs||fp||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|Let's say the auction begins:|

ht|f|cs|6|at|^b{|ia|o2C2D2H2S|at|}|ht|f|at|^j@2
Once responder eschews a double negative, all bids are natural and game-forcing.|
PG| ***** 38 ***** |


ht|k|AT|^B@2
What if responder raises the opener:|

ht|m|cs|6|at|^b{|ia|o2C2D2H3H|at|}|HT|m|at|^jor|ht|m|cs|6|at|^l{|ia|o2C2D2H4H|at|}|ht|q|at|^b@2
Both of these are game-forcing (especially since one of the bids is game!). But, which shows more?

Have you heard of "fast arrival?" This principle says: "Once you are forced to game, jumping to the game is actually weaker." The "fast arrival" into game (4@H) says: "Partner, I am dead minimum, interested only in game. If you bid again, do so because you have extras." Accordingly, the slower bid of raising to 3@H shows extras and slam interest. The logic is that with slam interest you should leave the most room for exploration.|
PG| ***** 39 ***** |


NT||bt||
