cs|6|AT|

^-{    2C-2D Waiting - 2nd Negative by Howard Schutzman   }
^-|cs||cp||cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|If you want to play the complete set of 2nd negatives recommended by Larry Cohen (3@C over 2@H or 2@S, 3@D over 3@C, and 3@H over 3@D) that is very reasonable. But I have a slightly different approach. I do like 3@C as 2nd negative over 2@H or 2@S. But I play there is no way to show a bust hand over 3@C or 3@D.|
PG| ***** 40 ***** |


AT|

First of all, I strain not to open 2@C and then rebid 3 of a minor. I will usually either rebid 2N or not open 2@C. So, for me, the auctions 2@C-2@D-3@C and 2@C-2@D-3@D almost never come up. And second of all, because the auction is already at such a high level (our first natural bid is at the 3-level) I think it is more important to be able to bid naturally and preserve space. |
PG| ***** 41 ***** |


AT|

So I am willing to give up the ability to show a bust hand. Bust hands, even over 2C openers, are pretty rare. So I don't worry about the very rare case where there is a 2@C opener followed by a 3 of a minor rebid and responder has a bust hand. |
PG| ***** 42 ***** |


AT|

I just bid naturally over 3 of a minor. If responder has a bust hand, so be it. You are still more likely than not to end up in the right place because responder can bid natural suits.|
pg| ***** 43 ***** |


NT||bt||

